In contrast to the Hadean to Paleoarchean interval extant rocks not heated to amphibolite grade are preserved at numerous sites to study the Ediacaran-Cambrian dynamo. Recalling equations (2)–(4) our criteria for robust data defining the mean state of the past geomagnetic field from these extant rocks include (i) time averaging (ii) Thellier paleointensity analyses and (iii) samples with single-domain-like magnetic particles. Time averaging over many tens of thousands of years is needed to exceed the influence of short-term fluctuations to confidently recover changes in the dipole signal, and hence this represents criterion (i). This can be achieved by sampling many time-independent dikes or lavas and ensuring that paleointensity data represent dispersion of the field [13,14,21,22], or by sampling intrusive rocks that cooled slowly. Bono et al. [18] took the latter approach by sampling the slowly cooled anorthosites of the Sept Îles intrusive suite [82] that cooled over at least \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
